      <link>https://duragauge.github.io/chapter-3/3.3/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://duragauge.github.io/chapter-3/3.3/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div style=&#34;position:relative; clear:both; padding:0;&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;  &lt;img src=&#34;https://duragauge.github.io/img/chapter-3/371919441_51f06c8fb9_b.jpg&#34;  title=&#34;Photo by john allspaw&#34;  alt=&#34;Photo by john allspaw&#34; style=&#34;display:block; width:100%; height:auto;&#34; &gt;&#xD;&#xA;  &lt;span style=&#34;position:absolute; height:auto; bottom:0em; right:0em; margin:0;  padding: .1em .3em;  color:white;  font-size: .8em;  background:rgba(0, 0, 0, 1);  text-align:right;  z-index:5;  opacity:0.65;  border-radius:.3em 0em 0em 0em;&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;a href = &#34;https://flic.kr/p/ySbGa&#34;&gt;Photo by john allspaw&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&#xD;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xD;&#xA;&lt;br&gt;&#xD;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;introduction&#34;&gt;Introduction&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Up until the invention of scientific calculators&#xA;&lt;label for=&#34;sn-HP-35&#34; class=&#34;margin-toggle sidenote-number&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;/label&gt;&#xA;&lt;input type=&#34;checkbox&#34; id=&#34;sn-HP-35&#34; class=&#34;margin-toggle&#34; /&gt;&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;sidenote&#34;&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://duragauge.github.io/img/chapter-3/4368541979_ec395ea1eb_o.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;HP-35 scientific calculator&#34;&gt;The HP-35 was the first handheld scientific calculator.  Developed by Hewlett-Packard, it went on sale in 1972 for $395.  &lt;a href=&#34;https://flic.kr/p/7E2Vki&#34;&gt;Photo by Julian Bucknall&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;in the 1970&#39;s, people relied on 300-year-old mechanical calculators called &amp;quot;slide rules&amp;quot;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
